# Audit items - what exactly the scanner is auditing right now

The **Audit items** tab shows a list of items the scanner has taken into the active audit. An audit item is, roughly speaking, an individual HTTP request (a base request to some point of the application) that Burp processes: it inserts payloads into it across all the insertion points found and runs a set of checks. The list fills up and updates as the scan goes - this is your window into "what's being audited this very second and where it's stuck". The tab is present only for tasks with an audit phase.

## Table columns

Each row is one audit item, and the columns show everything about its state:

- **#** - sequence number;
- **Host** - the destination host;
- **URL** - the destination URL;
- **Status** - the status: audit in progress or finished;
- **Passive phases / Active phases / JavaScript phases** - indicators of the check phases passed (see below);
- **Issues** - how many problems were found for this item, broken down by severity;
- **Requests** - how many requests were sent as part of the item's audit;
- **Errors** - network errors;
- **Insertion points** - how many insertion points were created;
- **Scanned insertion points** - how many of them were actually checked (fully or in a "lightened" way);
- **Start time / End time** - the start and end time of the item's audit;
- **Comment** - your note (editable with a double click).

## Audit phases

The phase summary helps you understand at which stage a specific item got stuck. The scanner runs an item through several groups of phases:

- **Passive phases** - passive phases: they find problems from already available data and consolidate findings;
- **Active phases** - active phases: they probe insertion points with payloads, catch stored behavior and second-order vulnerabilities;
- **JavaScript phases** - analysis of DOM-based problems (self-contained, reflected, stored).

## Item details and context menu

Clicking a row opens the details at the bottom: the base request and a list of all the insertion points for it (toggling with the display of the base response). Detail on insertion points is in a separate entry.

Right-clicking an item gives actions:

- **Show details** - open a separate window with the request/response and the **Inspector**;
- view the insertion points;
- **Cancel auditing** - cancel the audit of this item;
- **Audit again** - duplicate and re-audit;
- add/change a comment, highlight with a color;
- send the base request to other tools (**Repeater**, **Intruder**, etc.).

## Practice

> If the scan is dragging on forever - sort by **Requests** or by **Status**. An item with a huge number of requests and a "in progress" status is your candidate for the stuck point (often it's a bloated form with a heap of insertion points or an endpoint that's stalling). You can cancel it via **Cancel auditing** so the scan moves on.

> The **Scanned insertion points** column being smaller than **Insertion points** is normal: Burp audits frequently occurring points in a "lightened" way, and skips some points based on settings (see the entry on insertion points).

# Issues - the list of vulnerabilities found

The **Issues** tab is the findings themselves: potential vulnerabilities the task discovered. Each issue is stored in the project file along with accompanying information for analysis and remediation. The feature belongs to **Professional** (automatic vulnerability discovery is a Pro thing).

## Where to look

- **Project-wide:** **Dashboard** -> select **All issues** in the dock at the bottom.
- **For a specific task:** **Dashboard** -> select the task in **Tasks** -> the **Issues** tab.

## Table columns

- **Time** - the time of discovery;
- **Source** - which task found it;
- **Issue type** - the type of vulnerability;
- **Host** - the host;
- **Path** - the URL path (if applicable);
- **Insertion point** - the insertion point / parameter (if applicable);
- **Severity** - the severity: **High**, **Medium**, **Low**, **Information**;
- **Confidence** - the confidence: **Tentative**, **Firm**, **Certain**;
- **Comment** - a note (double click to edit).

Important: each problem is recorded only on its FIRST discovery - repeated triggers of the same type at the same point don't spawn duplicates, but instead supplement the existing issue with evidence.

## Filtering and search

There's a filter above the list that helps clear out the noise:

- by **Severity** levels;
- by **Confidence** levels;
- by check type: **BChecks**, scan checks, extensions, manually created ones;
- a text search bar.

## Detail panel

You select an issue - tabs appear at the bottom:

- **Advisory** - a description of the problem and remediation recommendations;
- **Request** - the request with the payload that triggered it (if any);
- **Response** - the response with the location of the problem highlighted (if any);
- **Path to issue** - the sequence of scanner actions that led to the finding (if any).

## Context menu

Right-click an issue:

- **Add comment** - add a comment;
- **Highlight** - highlight with a color;
- **Set severity** - change the severity (including marking as a **false positive**);
- **Set confidence** - change the confidence;
- **Delete issue** - delete;
- **Report selected issues** - export the selected ones to a report;
- **Restore original value** - restore the original severity/confidence if you changed them.

## Practice

```
Sort by Severity+Confidence -> High/Certain on top -> start with those.
For each issue:
  Advisory -> understood the essence and the location
  Request  -> right-click Send to Repeater -> reproduced it by hand
  confirmed -> into the report; not confirmed -> Set severity = False positive
```

> Pitfall: the scanner produces false positives, especially on reflected things and issues marked **Tentative/Firm**. Don't write anything into the report until you've reproduced it by hand in **Repeater**. **Certain** is usually more reliable, but it's worth eyeballing that too.

# Event log - the event log and the first place to debug

The **Event log** records key events while the task is running. When a scan "isn't working", is stuck, or is spitting out errors - this is the first place you look: it tells you in plain text what went wrong.

## Where to look

- **Project-wide:** **Dashboard** -> select **Event log** in the dock at the bottom.
- **For a specific task:** **Dashboard** -> select the task in **Tasks** -> the **Event log** tab.

## Columns

- **Time** - the time of the event;
- **Type** - the level: **Critical**, **Error**, **Info**, **Debug**;
- **Source** - what generated the event (task number or tool name);
- **Message** - a brief description.

## Event levels

Four levels: **Critical**, **Error**, **Info**, **Debug**. In practice **Critical** and **Error** are primarily of interest - these are real problems. **Info**/**Debug** are background noise, useful for deep analysis.

## Filtering and management

- the level toggle buttons above the log (leave only **Critical/Error** on a noisy project);
- a search bar (for example, by task number), sorting, copying column data;
- selecting an entry expands the **detail panel** at the bottom - there's an extended description and recommendations for fixing the cause there;
- right-click an entry -> **Clear event log** - clear the entire log.

## What you usually see here when there are problems

- connection and TLS errors with the target;
- messages about scope ("out of scope");
- nothing but timeouts / the host refusing to respond;
- confirmation that the task actually started and isn't hanging silently.

## Practice

```
Scan finds nothing / is stuck:
  1. Event log -> filter Critical+Error
  2. read the Message -> most often: scope, auth, TLS, timeout
  3. didn't understand the error text -> check against the "Burp Scanner error reference"
```

> To decode specific error messages, PortSwigger has a separate "Burp Scanner error reference" - if the error text is unclear, look it up there.

# Audit log - the chronology of findings' lives during the audit

The **Audit log** is a feed of events related specifically to issues during the audit phase. Unlike the **Event log** (which is about the task's work in general: connections, errors, progress), the **Audit log** answers the question "what happened to the findings themselves". The tab is present only for tasks with an audit.

What gets written here:

- when Burp finds a new issue;
- when Burp adds new evidence to an already known issue;
- when Burp discovers that an issue is no longer there and removes it from the **Issues** list.

## Where to look

**Dashboard** -> select the task in **Tasks** -> the **Audit log** tab.

## Columns

- **#** - the entry number;
- **Time** - the time;
- **Source** - the source task;
- **Action** - the action: found / removed / evidence added;
- **Issue type** - the type of problem;
- **Host** - the host;
- **Path** - the URL path (if applicable);
- **Insertion point** - the insertion point (if applicable);
- **Severity** - the severity (High/Medium/Low/Information);
- **Confidence** - the confidence (Tentative/Firm/Certain);
- **Comment** - a note (double click).

## Filter, details, actions

As in **Issues**: a filter by **Severity**, **Confidence**, check type (**BChecks**, scan checks, extensions) and a search bar.

Selecting an entry expands the tabs: **Advisory**, **Request**, **Response**, **Path to issue**. Through the **Audit log** you can also view the details of interactions with the **Burp Collaborator** server (for out-of-band findings).

Right-click: **Add comment**, **Highlight**, **Set severity**, **Set confidence**, **Report selected issues**, **Restore original value**.

## How it's useful in practice

> Want to see findings in the order they appeared in time (rather than grouped by type, as in **Issues**) - look at the **Audit log**. Handy for tracking fresh issues right during the scan and going off to triage them immediately.

> An entry with **Action = removed** (the issue disappeared) is a reason to pause and think: the problem was unstable/intermittent or depended on the application's state. Sometimes it's worth re-checking by hand before writing it off.
